main event: A large, white, oblong object was observed in Roseberg, Oregon on 5 November 1957. The object backed off towards the ocean and eventually faded from sight after a 20 to 30 minute observation.
interesting points: The observation lasted for a significant duration of 20 to 30 minutes, allowing for detailed examination of the object.
Despite the lack of azimuth data, Venus's position in the southwest at approximately 20 degrees elevation at the reported time raises questions about the astronomical nature of the sighting.
The source of the sighting was a civilian, adding credibility to the report.
The senior controller on duty, Major Charles W. Finnegan, believed the sighting to be of an unidentified flying object, indicating the seriousness of the observation.
The absence of photographs and insufficient data prevented a conclusive evaluation of the sighting.
